{"title_page": "Neon (distributor)", "text_new": "{{Use American English|date=February 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2018}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name             = Neon\n| logo             = File:Neon (distributor) logo.svg\n| type             = [[Privately held company|Private]]\n| founder          = Tom Quinn<br/>[[Tim League]]\n| area_served      = Worldwide\n| key_people       = Kim Kalyka (Vice president)<ref name=\"NeonLink\"/>\n| industry         = [[Film industry]]\n| revenue          = \n| operating_income = \n| net_income       = \n| owner            = \n| location_city    = [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]]\n| location_country = U.S.\n| num_locations    = \n| num_employees    = 11-50 people<ref name=\"NeonLink\">{{cite web|url=https://www.linkedin.com/company/neonrated?trk=similar-companies_org_image|title=Neon|publisher=LinkedIn|accessdate=May 30, 2018}}</ref>\n| parent           = \n| caption          = \n| divisions        = BH Tilt (with [[Blumhouse Productions]])\n| foundation       = {{Start date and age|2017|01|13}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2017/01/tom-quinn-tim-league-launch-neon-distribution-company-sundance-film-festival-1201885413/|title=Tom Quinn & Tim League Launch Distribution Shingle Neon For Sundance|first=Mike Fleming|last=Jr|date=January 13, 2017|publisher=}}</ref>\n| homepage         = {{URL|http://neonrated.com}}\n}}\n'''Neon''' (stylized as '''NEON''') is an American [[film production]] and [[film distribution|distribution]] company founded by Tom Quinn and [[Tim League]] in 2017. The company is best known for releasing films, such as ''[[Ingrid Goes West]]'', ''[[Beach Rats]]'', ''[[I, Tonya]]'', and ''[[Parasite (2019 film)|Parasite]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2018/05/neon-tom-quinn-disruptors-commentary-news-1202382220/amp/|title=Why NEON Is The Hot New Distributor In Town \u2014 Deadline Disruptors|date=May 13, 2018|publisher=}}</ref> In September 2017, the company partnered with [[Blumhouse Productions]] to manage BH Tilt.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/blumhouse-bh-tilt-neon-1202550069/|title=Blumhouse Partners With Neon to Manage BH Tilt Label|first=Dave|last=McNary|date=September 7, 2017|publisher=}}</ref> {{As of|2019}}, League is no longer involved with daily operations for the company.<ref>{{cite news|url = https://www.nytimes.com/2019/11/27/business/media/parasite-movie-studio-neon.html|title = \u2018Parasite\u2019 Has Shocked the Box Office, Helped by an Upstart Studio\n|work = [[The New York Times]]|date = November 27, 2019|accessdate = February 13, 2020|last = Sperling|first = Nicole}}</ref>\n\n==Process==\nDuring the 4th Annual Zurich Summit, Tom Quinn commented on Neon's intent to release titles that appeal to audiences who \"skew under 45, that have no aversion to violence, no aversion to foreign language and to non-fiction.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=MacNab|first1=Geoffrey|title=How new US distribution outfit Neon is chasing younger audiences|url=https://www.screendaily.com/news/-how-new-us-distribution-outfit-neon-is-chasing-younger-audiences/5122827.article|accessdate=April 18, 2018|work=[[Screendaily.com|Screen International]]|date=October 1, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Accolades==\n{{As of|2020|2}}, Neon has received a total of 12 [[Academy Award]] nominations. In 2018, ''[[I, Tonya]]'' received three nominations, winning [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actress|Best Supporting Actress]] for [[Allison Janney]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/allison-janney-wins-oscar-best-supporting-actress-1202716076/|title=Allison Janney on Oscar Win: \u2018I Did It All by Myself\u2019|last=Lopez|first=Ricardo|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=March 4, 2018|accessdate=February 10, 2020}}</ref> In 2019, ''[[Border (2018 film)|Border]]'' was nominated for [[Academy Award for Best Makeup and Hairstyling|Best Makeup and Hairstyling]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailydot.com/parsec/border-movie-oscars/|title=The weirdest movie at the Oscars is \u2018Border\u2019|last=Baker-Whitelaw|first=Gavia|work=[[The Daily Dot]]|date=February 19, 2019|accessdate=February 10, 2020}}</ref> In 2020, Neon experienced its most successful Oscar season yet with ''[[Parasite (2019 film)|Parasite]]'' and ''[[Honeyland (2019 film)|Honeyland]]'' accruing eight nominations in total, with the former winning four awards including [[Academy Award for Best Picture|Best Picture]], becoming the first non-English language film to receive that honor.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/2/9/21130625/oscars-parasite-best-picture-win-bong-joon-ho-historic-academy-awards-2020|title=Parasite wins Best Picture, making Oscar history|last=Alexander|first=Julia|work=[[The Verge]]|date=February 9, 2020|accessdate=February 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Released===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Year\n! Film\n! Director\n! Release date\n! Notes\n! {{Abbr|Ref.|References}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"7\" | 2017\n| ''[[Colossal (film)|Colossal]]''\n| [[Nacho Vigalondo]]\n| April 7, 2017\n|\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thewrap.com/anne-hathaways-colossal-picked-up-by-tom-quinn-and-tim-leagues-new-distributor/|title=Anne Hathaway's 'Colossal' to Be Released by Tom Quinn and Tim League's New Distributor|publisher=[[TheWrap]]|first=Beatrice|last=Verhoeven|date=September 14, 2016|accessdate=January 13, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Risk (2016 film)|Risk]]''\n| [[Laura Poitras]]\n| May 5, 2017\n|\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2017/04/risk-trailer-showtime-laura-poitras-citizenfour-director-1202065030/|title='Risk': Neon Sets Theatrical Bow For WikiLeaks Docu From 'Citizenfour' Director Ahead Of Showtime Premiere \u2013 Update|first=Erik|last=Pedersen|date=April 18, 2017|publisher=}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[The Bad Batch]]''\n| [[Ana Lily Amirpour]]\n| June 23, 2017\n|\n|\n|-\n| ''[[The B-Side: Elsa Dorfman's Portrait Photography]]''\n| [[Errol Morris]]\n| June 30, 2017\n|\n|<ref>{{cite web|